        "concerns": [
          "We noticed GAMCN CGCC Macon's patient delays remain the critical outlier: at 38.4 minutes, they sit 64% above the company average of 23.39 minutes despite strong scheduler compliance at 85.7%. The data suggests a disconnect between scheduling discipline and actual patient flow; one area worth exploring together is whether nurse-to-chair assignment ratios or chair sequencing patterns are creating bottlenecks that high scheduler compliance alone cannot resolve. INHAR Harcourt's chair utilization at 110.7% reflects ongoing overbooking; while the gradual normalization toward 100% would be healthy, we should partner to ensure this adjustment does not erode the gains in treatments past closing that were achieved in March."
        ],
        "recommendations": [
          "We recommend GAMCN CGCC Macon audit its scheduling templates and nurse-to-chair assignment workflows to identify why scheduler compliance at 85.7% is not translating to shorter patient delays. A review of appointment duration estimates and chair turnover time\u2014especially for high-complexity treatments\u2014may reveal whether the templates are misaligned with actual clinical demand, and a pilot of targeted iAssign training for nursing staff could strengthen real-time load balancing across chairs, directly addressing the 38.4-minute delay that exceeds company average by 64%."
